As of March 2023, there are no licensed treatments specifically approved for the treatment of Ebola virus disease (EVD), which is an often-fatal viral infection that can cause fever, vomiting, diarrhea, and internal and external bleeding. However, some experimental therapies have shown promise in clinical trials and are sometimes used on a compassionate-use basis in people with EVD.  These treatments include:

ZMapp: This is a combination of three monoclonal antibodies (mAbs) that target different parts of the Ebola virus. In a clinical trial conducted during the 2014-2016 West African Ebola outbreak, ZMapp was found to be safe and may have improved survival rates among people with EVD when given early in the course of the disease. However, the trial was not designed to prove that ZMapp was responsible for the better outcomes.

Remdesivir: This is a broad-spectrum antiviral drug that has been shown to be effective against several viruses, including Ebola. In a clinical trial conducted during the 2018 Ebola outbreak in the Democratic Republic of Congo, remdesivir was found to be safe and may have improved survival rates among people with EVD when given early in the course of the disease. However, the trial was not designed to prove that remdesivir was responsible for the better outcomes.

Convalescent plasma: This is plasma obtained from people who have recovered from Ebola virus infection and who have developed antibodies against the virus. Convalescent plasma has been used on a compassionate-use basis in people with EVD, but its effectiveness has not yet been proven in well-designed clinical trials.

It's important to note that even if an experimental treatment shows promise in early trials, it may not be effective or safe when used in a broader population or in different settings. Moreover, there is still a lot that we don't know about Ebola virus disease, and new treatments may emerge

Amanda Peet, an actress best known for her starring roles in The Whole Nine Yards and The Sopranos, has revealed that she uses the term "special hug" to explain sex to her young daughter. In an interview with People magazine, Peet explained that she and her husband, screenwriter David Benioff, have been trying to find age-appropriate ways to talk about sex with their children.

To explain sex to her daughter, who is now 6 years old, Peet said that she has used the term "special hug." "We've said, 'When a mommy and daddy love each other very much, they have a special hug,'" Peet said. "But it's not like we dwell on it." Peet also said that she and Benioff have tried to be open and honest about sex with their children, while still keeping things age-appropriate. 

While the term "special hug" may be an effective way to explain sex to a young child, it's important to remember that as children get older, they may need more detailed and accurate information about sex and sexuality. It's also important to be respectful of each child's individual developmental level and comfort level when it comes to talking about sex.

1. Get organized - Gather all the necessary documents, such as W-2s, 1099s, and receipts, and make sure they are complete and accurate before you start.

3. Take advantage of free filing options - If your income is below a certain threshold, you may be eligible to file your taxes for free through the IRS Free File program or a volunteer tax assistance program.
4. Hire a professional - If you have a complex tax situation, it may be worth considering hiring a tax professional, such as an accountant or a tax preparer, to help you navigate the process.
5. File early - Filing your taxes early can help you avoid any last-minute stress and potentially receive your refund faster.

9 Delicious Vegetable Recipes To Try Tonight

Vegetables are an essential part of a healthy diet, but they can sometimes be boring or bland. Here are 9 delicious vegetable recipes that will make you enjoy eating your veggies:

1. Roasted Carrots with Thyme and Honey: Preheat your oven to 425°F and toss sliced carrots with olive oil, thyme, honey, salt, and pepper. Roast for 25-30 minutes, until tender and caramelized.

2. Sautéed Kale with Garlic and Lemon: Heat some olive oil in a large skillet over medium heat. Add minced garlic and stir until fragrant. Add chopped kale and sauté until wilted. Finish with a squeeze of lemon juice and a sprinkle of red pepper flakes.

3. Grilled Zucchini and Yellow Squash: Slice zucchini and yellow squash into ¼-inch-thick rounds. Brush with olive oil and sprinkle with salt and pepper. Grill over medium heat for 3-4 minutes per side, until tender and slightly charred.

4. Roasted Cauliflower with Curry Yogurt Sauce: Cut a head of cauliflower into florets and toss with olive oil, curry powder, cumin, salt, and pepper. Roast at 425°F for 25-30 minutes, until tender and slightly browned. Serve with a yogurt sauce made with Greek yogurt, lemon juice, curry powder, and salt.

5. Baked Sweet Potato Fries: Preheat your oven to 425°F and line a baking sheet with parchment paper. Slice sweet potatoes into fries and toss with olive oil, salt, and pepper. Bake for 20-25 minutes, until crispy on the outside and tender on the inside.

6. Roasted Brussels Sprouts with Bacon: Cut Brussels sprouts in half and toss with chopped bacon, olive oil, salt, and pepper. Roast at 425°F for 25-30 minutes, until crispy and caramelized.
